(n-wu, was surrounded by a great army under Erh-\015)'
(chu Chao and others.  His own force was comparatively small,\015)'
(consisting only of 2000 horse and something under 30,000 foot.\015)'
(The lines of investment had not been drawn very closely together,\015)'
(gaps being left at certain points.  But Kao Huan,  instead of\015)'
(trying to escape,  actually made a shift to block all the\015)'
(remaining outlets himself by driving into them a number of oxen\015)'
(and donkeys roped together.  As soon as his officers and men saw\015)'
(that there was nothing for it but to conquer or die,  their\015)'
(spirits rose to an extraordinary pitch of exaltation,  and they\015)'
(charged with such desperate ferocity that the opposing ranks\015)'
(broke and crumbled under their onslaught.]\015)'
(\015)'
(On desperate ground,  I would proclaim to my soldiers the\015)'
(hopelessness of saving their lives.\015)'
(\015)'
(     Tu Yu says:  "Burn your baggage and impedimenta, throw away\015)'
(your stores and provisions, choke up the wells,  destroy your\015)'
(cooking-stoves,  and make it plain to your men that they cannot\015)'
(survive, but must fight to the death."  Mei Yao-ch`en says:  "The\015)'
(only chance of life lies in giving up all hope of it."   This\015)'
(concludes what Sun Tzu has to say about  "grounds"  and the\015)'
("variations" corresponding to them.  Reviewing the passages which\015)'
(bear on this important subject, we cannot fail to be struck by\015)'
(the desultory and unmethodical fashion in which it is treated.\015)'
(Sun Tzu begins abruptly in VIII. ss. 2 to enumerate  "variations"\015)'
(before touching on "grounds" at all, but only mentions five,\015)'
(namely nos. 7, 5, 8 and 9 of the subsequent list, and one that is\015)'
(not included in it.  A few varieties of ground are dealt with in\015)'
(the earlier portion of chap. IX, and then chap. X sets forth six\015)'
(new grounds, with six variations of plan to match.  None of these\015)'
(is   mentioned   again,  though the first is hardly   to   be\015)'
(distinguished from ground no. 4 in the next chapter.  At last, in\015)'
(chap. XI, we come to the Nine Grounds par excellence, immediately\015)'
(followed by the variations.  This takes us down to ss.  14.  In\015)'
(SS. 43-45, fresh definitions are provided for nos. 5, 6, 2, 8 and\015)'
(9  \(in the order given\), as well as for the tenth ground noticed\015)'
(in chap. VIII; and finally, the nine variations are enumerated\015)'
(once more from beginning to end, all, with the exception of 5,  6\015)'
(and 7, being different from those previously given.  Though it is\015)'
(impossible to account for the present state of Sun Tzu's text,  a\015)'
(few suggestive facts maybe brought into prominence:   \(1\)  Chap.\015)'
(VIII,  according to the title, should deal with nine variations,\015)'
(whereas only five appear.  \(2\) It is an abnormally short chapter.\015)'
(\(3\) Chap. XI is entitled The Nine Groun)'
